  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety that students from groups historically underrepresented in science and technology fields experience when they are reminded of negative stereotypes about their group's abilities. As a retired man who grew up in Washington DC and attended only primary school, I can see how this issue plays out in real life. In my time, when I was a young boy, the idea that girls couldn't do math or boys couldn't do art was common. Today, this mindset still affects many students. I believe we should address it because it limits potential and creates unnecessary stress. The way to do this is by promoting inclusive teaching methods and encouraging students to see themselves as capable in all subjects. For example, in my neighborhood, when I read novels about diverse scientists, it helped me realize that anyone can be a scientist. I've also seen how board games can help children understand teamwork and problem-solving without the pressure of competition. The key is to create a welcoming environment where everyone feels they belong. By focusing on individual strengths and not group stereotypes, we can help students thrive in STEM. It's important to remember that education should be about growth, not fear.",
